Thank you...Edison Athletic Department

This Thursday (May 21, 2020), Bailey & Hamilton Elementary parents will need to drop off the second learning packet to your child's school between 2:00pm and 6:00pm. Please follow the car rider drop off procedures during the return of learning packets.

In addition, student personal items will be returned to you during the learning packet drop off. Hamilton School will distribute Spring pictures and yearbooks as well.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact your child’s classroom teacher or call our LSCS Helpline at 219-230-4596.

To Our Seniors,

We wish the end of your senior year was different. We wanted the opportunity to watch you enjoy all the joyous activities that occur at the end of your senior year. Since the situation doesn't allow us to do as planned, just like with anything in life, we adjust. To let you know we are thinking of you, and are proud of you, we will be delivering this yard sign to your home in the next week or so!!! We are also thinking of other ways we can honor and celebrate you so continue to check your email for updates. As for graduation, we are waiting a few more weeks before we decide what type of graduation ceremony we will be having to honor you, but rest assured no matter what, we will be having something memorable to celebrate your accomplishments!! Keep up the good work with eLearning and finish strong!!!! #EaglesStrong

Today is Census Day in America!

During these difficult times, it is important to keep functioning in as normal a capacity as possible and keep our eye on important goals and targets that were our focus before the pandemic—this includes the 2020 Census. The #2020Census count is important now more than ever, as it will help determine the allotment of representation and funding which will help Indiana's re-growth and recovery from the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic.

Residents can still fill out the Census by phone, by mail, and online. #EveryHoosierChildCounts

Watch this 2 minute YouTube Video about the importance of participating in the 2020Census. https://youtu.be/wV0BilOlrQA

View the 2020 Census online at: https://my2020census.gov/

From the Athletic Department:
The Boys’ Varsity Basketball Sectional Tournament opening game, will take place on Tuesday March 3rd at 6:00pm at Thea Bowman Leadership Academy in Gary versus Gary Roosevelt. Ticket Prices are $6.00 each game or $10.00 for the entire sectional tournament. Fans are to enter Door C at Thea Bowman Leadership Academy. If our Fighting Eagles win this first round game, we will play the second round game on Friday, March 6th at 5:30pm at Thea Bowman Academy versus Whiting High School. Parking is limited at Thea Bowman Academy, so please arrive early to insure getting a good parking spot. For sectional games on Friday March 6th and Saturday March 7th, Thea Bowman Academy will have an overflow parking lot at Tri-City Plaza, located next to Thea Bowman Academy. A shuttle service will be used to transport fans to Thea Bowman Academy from this location. Come out and support our Fighting Eagles Boys’ Varsity Basketball Team as they compete in the IHSAA Indiana State Basketball Tournament! GO FIGHTING EAGLES!!

We are so happy that Lake Station student, Mieka Neely, was able to represent Lake County at the VOICE Youth Day of Action on January 27th. VOICE is Indiana’s statewide youth empowerment brand, whose initiative is to engage, educate, and empower teens to celebrate a tobacco-free lifestyle. They were among students from across Indiana that got to speak with Governor Holcomb, Indiana State Health Commissioner Dr. Box, Senator Melton, Actor Moses Jones and a host of other legislators and community leaders. We are so proud of Mieka to be willing to raise her voice to save lives.

From the Eagle's Nest
February 11 at 11:51 AM ·

Learning Lab: Extreme X-Rays and Particle Accelerators

Chemistry students in Mr. Ness' class at Edison participated in a Learning Lab at Argonne National Laboratory. Student teams designed a magnetic linear accelerator using a Gauss gun. They investigated concepts in magnetism and energy transfer, collected data, and optimized their design based on previous results. By observing relationships and patterns in their data, students made thoughtful modifications in a friendly competition to see which team can achieve the greatest acceleration.

post_text: Middle School French students in Ms. Dokich's class use WhisperPhones to read their Free Writes to each other. Every Wednesday, the students complete Free Writes in which they have 10 minutes to write a story or answer a question in French. The goal was to average 60 words per student in the month of January. They wrote a total of 26,123 words for the month! A monthly average of 253.5 words per student or 63.4 words per student per week. Great job meeting your goal Eagles! This month, the Free Write in French Challenge rises to 70 words. Go Eagles!

Thank you, and have a great rest of your weekend.

The Hamilton Science Bowl team has been working hard at practices to prepare for competition. The Hamilton Science Bowl Academic team is made of 4th and 5th grade students and is guided by Mrs. Burkett. The science bowl experiment was to extract banana DNA. They also extracted strawberry DNA just for fun. The standards used in science bowl 2020 are Life Sciences and Cellular Biology. The team competition takes place Tuesday, January, 28th during practice after school. The experiment and individual rounds take place Wednesday, January, 29th during school. Good Luck Hamilton Science Bowl Team!

Indiana Coalition for Public Education
November 17, 2019 at 4:50 PM ·

Truth bomb from our state superintendent Dr. Jennifer McCormick!

Who is REALLY to blame for the lack of MONEY for teacher pay (and nurses, counselors, social workers, bus drivers)? The STATE holds the pursestrings. They spent $160 million on vouchers last year on vouchers to schools that can openly discriminate! How much did the virtual charter school flush down the toilet when they cheated Hoosier taxpayers? How much is it we waste on testing? Where does the money go? Let's talk accountability, shall we?

#RememberNextNovember

From the Eagle's Nest
November 4, 2019 at 4:55 PM ·

How would you like to earn a free or discounted yearbook? It’s easy! The Edison Jr-Sr High yearbook is holding a fundraiser. Items such as cookie dough and lava cakes are for sale. For each item sold, the student will receive $2 off the price of a yearbook. So for example, if he or she sells 10 items, the student will have earned a $20 credit towards the purchase of a book! Brochures can be picked up today from Mr. Pagán in room 220. The current cost for yearbooks is: Middle School 6-8 for $25.00 and high school 9-12 for $45.
